1
00:00:01,617 --> 00:00:02,097
Speaker 26: Hi, everyone.

2
00:00:02,297 --> 00:00:02,977
Thanks for joining.

3
00:00:04,218 --> 00:00:05,057
I'm Ankur Aggarwal.

4
00:00:05,317 --> 00:00:08,077
I'm a software engineer
at Meta, where I work on

5
00:00:08,237 --> 00:00:10,018
privacy-preserving AI infrastructure.

6
00:00:11,197 --> 00:00:14,457
Today, I want to talk about something
that I think is one of the most

7
00:00:14,537 --> 00:00:19,637
important unsolved problems in the
agentic AI stack, which is: How do

8
00:00:19,677 --> 00:00:24,917
we secure the data flows between
AI agents and databases, especially

9
00:00:25,018 --> 00:00:29,577
when those agents are running inside
confidential compu-compute environments?

10
00:00:30,257 --> 00:00:30,938
That's a mouthful.

11
00:00:31,417 --> 00:00:35,977
So let me break down what actually it
means over the next twenty minutes or so.

12
00:00:37,198 --> 00:00:38,417
Let's start with the problem first.

13
00:00:39,077 --> 00:00:42,597
Over the past couple of years,
confidential computing has made enormous

14
00:00:42,637 --> 00:00:48,904
progress Thanks to Meta, we now have
trusted execution environments, TEEs,

15
00:00:49,374 --> 00:00:54,634
that can run full large language model
inside verified isolated enclaves.

16
00:00:55,274 --> 00:01:00,154
The model runs, and nobody outside
that enclave can see what it's doing.

17
00:01:01,114 --> 00:01:01,554
That's good.

18
00:01:02,233 --> 00:01:02,854
But here's the thing.

19
00:01:03,614 --> 00:01:07,174
The moment that model needs to do
something useful, for instance, query a

20
00:01:07,214 --> 00:01:13,394
database, call an external API, or invoke
a tool, the security boundary collapses.

21
00:01:13,434 --> 00:01:14,424
Think about it.

22
00:01:14,434 --> 00:01:16,434
You have spent millions
of dollars engineering an

23
00:01:16,494 --> 00:01:18,244
isolated enclave for inference.

24
00:01:19,054 --> 00:01:23,934
Then your model issues a SQL query over a
plain text connection to a database that

25
00:01:23,973 --> 00:01:26,014
has no idea it's talking to an enclave.

26
00:01:26,734 --> 00:01:31,434
All that security work and the data
just walks out through the tool layer.

27
00:01:32,434 --> 00:01:36,674
This is the gap we are going to--
we're going to talk about today.

28
00:01:38,074 --> 00:01:42,814
Now, you might be thinking, "Okay, but
we always had APIs calling databases.

29
00:01:43,614 --> 00:01:47,894
What's so different about
agentic AI?" Three things make

30
00:01:47,934 --> 00:01:48,914
this fundamentally harder.

31
00:01:50,034 --> 00:01:51,634
First, multi-step reasoning.

32
00:01:52,754 --> 00:01:57,214
Unlike a traditional API call
that's fire and forget, an agent

33
00:01:57,274 --> 00:01:58,874
executes long reasoning chains.

34
00:01:59,774 --> 00:02:03,774
It might issue ten, fifteen, twenty
tool calls in a single workflow.

35
00:02:04,634 --> 00:02:08,494
Each one of those is a potential
data exfiltration vector.

36
00:02:09,634 --> 00:02:13,314
It's not one door to guard,
it's a hallway full of them.

37
00:02:14,754 --> 00:02:17,094
Second, live databases access.

38
00:02:17,954 --> 00:02:19,994
These agents aren't just
reading static files.

39
00:02:20,614 --> 00:02:23,694
They're querying structured
enterprise data in real time.

40
00:02:24,424 --> 00:02:26,853
Health records, financial
ledgers, legal documents.

41
00:02:27,444 --> 00:02:31,994
The sensitivity of what's being
accessed is extremely high.

42
00:02:32,054 --> 00:02:36,574
Third, and this is a subtle
one, cumulative leakage.

43
00:02:36,654 --> 00:02:38,474
No single query reveals everything.

44
00:02:38,534 --> 00:02:42,834
If you look at any individual tool
call, it might seem fine, but across a

45
00:02:42,853 --> 00:02:47,233
fifteen-step workflow, sensitive context
accumulates in the model context window.

46
00:02:47,914 --> 00:02:51,784
You can reconstruct a complete patient
record or a financial profile from

47
00:02:51,793 --> 00:02:54,874
fragments that individually look harmless.

48
00:02:55,794 --> 00:02:59,294
This is a new class of privacy risk
that traditional access controls

49
00:02:59,574 --> 00:03:00,774
w- weren't designed to handle.

50
00:03:03,466 --> 00:03:05,746
So let's discuss our roadmap for today.

51
00:03:06,606 --> 00:03:08,266
We'll, we'll be covering four things.

52
00:03:08,586 --> 00:03:12,806
First, why standard MCP, that's
the Model Context Protocol,

53
00:03:13,006 --> 00:03:14,606
breaks in secure environments.

54
00:03:15,346 --> 00:03:20,386
Second, I'll introduce Confidential
MCP or CMCP, the extension

55
00:03:20,406 --> 00:03:21,586
we have designed to fix this.

56
00:03:22,226 --> 00:03:26,826
Third, we'll go deep on two key
primitives: the anonymization transform

57
00:03:26,886 --> 00:03:29,486
layer and the attested egress policies.

58
00:03:30,046 --> 00:03:33,386
And fourth, we'll talk about
operational realities because

59
00:03:34,066 --> 00:03:37,146
architectural diagrams are great, but
production is where things get real.

60
00:03:38,046 --> 00:03:39,706
So let's strive-- let's dive in.

61
00:03:40,946 --> 00:03:43,646
Let's first discuss about what an MCP is.

62
00:03:43,946 --> 00:03:49,486
For those who are unfamiliar with it, the,
the Model Context Protocol is Anthropic's

63
00:03:49,546 --> 00:03:53,746
open standard for connecting LLM agents
to external tools and data sources.

64
00:03:54,166 --> 00:03:55,086
It's a great protocol.

65
00:03:55,766 --> 00:04:00,506
It defines how an agent discover tools,
calls them, and get results back.

66
00:04:01,286 --> 00:04:04,226
It is becoming a de facto
standard in the agentic AI space.

67
00:04:05,766 --> 00:04:13,986
However, and this is a critical
issue, MCP was designed for

68
00:04:14,026 --> 00:04:16,026
connected, trusted environments.

69
00:04:17,266 --> 00:04:21,706
It assumes that you are in a world
where endpoints can be freely inspected

70
00:04:21,745 --> 00:04:26,806
and where transport is inherently
trustworthy, where you can dynamically

71
00:04:26,846 --> 00:04:29,166
negotiate capabilities and runtime.

72
00:04:29,826 --> 00:04:33,386
None of those holds inside a TEE
operating under zero trust assumptions.

73
00:04:34,426 --> 00:04:38,146
When every interaction must be
authenticated, constrained, and privacy

74
00:04:38,206 --> 00:04:43,086
preserving by design, standard MCP becomes
a liability at the enclave boundary.

75
00:04:43,776 --> 00:04:47,646
It can expose metadata, weaken
policy enforcement, and create

76
00:04:47,746 --> 00:04:51,326
integration gaps that are very
difficult to close after the fact.

77
00:04:52,226 --> 00:04:57,186
What we need is a protocol layer
that treats the enclave perimeter

78
00:04:57,326 --> 00:05:01,766
as a hostile external interface,
not just at productive time, runtime

79
00:05:03,346 --> 00:05:04,885
And that's exactly what we built.

80
00:05:06,066 --> 00:05:08,546
Let me get specific about
where MCP breaks down.

81
00:05:09,546 --> 00:05:11,246
There are three fundamental weaknesses.

82
00:05:12,246 --> 00:05:14,506
Number one, transport security gaps.

83
00:05:15,546 --> 00:05:19,746
Standard MCP connection use TLS, which
is fine for encryption in transit,

84
00:05:20,726 --> 00:05:23,116
but TLS cannot prove enclave identity.

85
00:05:23,966 --> 00:05:27,866
It can't tell you the server on the
other end of that connection is actually

86
00:05:27,906 --> 00:05:30,306
executing inside a legitimate TEE.

87
00:05:31,466 --> 00:05:34,866
You need mutual attestation for
that, and MCP doesn't have it.

88
00:05:35,606 --> 00:05:40,286
So you end up with an encrypted channel
to do something, and you don't know what.

89
00:05:41,445 --> 00:05:44,126
Number two, dynamic
schema and tool discovery.

90
00:05:44,145 --> 00:05:48,346
Tool schemas and database schemas are
dis-- uh, are discovered at runtime.

91
00:05:49,025 --> 00:05:51,945
The agent says, "What tools
do you have?" And the server

92
00:05:51,955 --> 00:05:53,405
responds with a full manifest.

93
00:05:54,385 --> 00:05:56,666
In the confidential
context, this is a problem.

94
00:05:57,786 --> 00:06:00,106
That schema metadata is itself sensitive.

95
00:06:00,746 --> 00:06:04,445
It reveals what data exist,
what columns are available, and

96
00:06:04,506 --> 00:06:05,586
what the structure looks like.

97
00:06:06,486 --> 00:06:10,286
You've just created an unauthenticated
channel through which sensitive

98
00:06:10,346 --> 00:06:14,426
information can leak before any
actual query is even executed.

99
00:06:15,346 --> 00:06:17,586
And number three,
authentication mismatches.

100
00:06:18,466 --> 00:06:22,566
MCP's credential model
assumes ambient identity.

101
00:06:23,746 --> 00:06:30,686
OAuth token, API keys, bearer tokens,
but these don't have ambient identity.

102
00:06:30,726 --> 00:06:31,705
They have attestation.

103
00:06:32,655 --> 00:06:36,746
They can cryptographically prove what
code is running inside them, but they

104
00:06:36,786 --> 00:06:39,916
can't just present a bearer token
the way a regular service would.

105
00:06:40,806 --> 00:06:44,405
MCP has no native support for
attestation-based credential

106
00:06:44,445 --> 00:06:48,405
delegation, which means you're
left with awkward workarounds

107
00:06:48,466 --> 00:06:50,106
that undermine the security model.

108
00:06:51,096 --> 00:06:55,645
These three weaknesses together mean
that standard MCP is not a good fit

109
00:06:56,546 --> 00:07:00,586
for purpose-- for that purpose in
confidential compute environments

110
00:07:07,005 --> 00:07:07,985
So what do we do about it?

111
00:07:09,265 --> 00:07:12,906
We introduce confidential MCP or cMCP.

112
00:07:14,005 --> 00:07:18,604
cMCP is a backward compatible extension
to Anthropic's model context protocol.

113
00:07:18,945 --> 00:07:22,145
I want to emphasize that
word backward compatible.

114
00:07:24,065 --> 00:07:26,585
If you have existing MCP
tooling, it still works.

115
00:07:27,265 --> 00:07:29,985
We are not asking anyone,
anyone to rip and replace.

116
00:07:30,765 --> 00:07:35,044
cMCP adds new capabilities
on top of existing protocol.

117
00:07:35,724 --> 00:07:38,966
It's designed specifically for LLM
agents operating inside trusted

118
00:07:39,044 --> 00:07:43,405
execution environments that need
auditable, privacy-preserving

119
00:07:43,505 --> 00:07:45,105
access to tools and databases.

120
00:07:46,126 --> 00:07:50,365
The design draws on architecture
validated by Meta's WhatsApp private

121
00:07:50,426 --> 00:07:54,705
processing system and our broader
confidential computing practice.

122
00:07:55,786 --> 00:07:57,825
And it introduces three new primitives.

123
00:07:58,344 --> 00:08:03,385
One, a three-zone service topology
that defines clear trust boundaries.

124
00:08:04,044 --> 00:08:08,425
Two, an anonymization transform
layer that controls what data

125
00:08:08,465 --> 00:08:09,885
the model can actually see.

126
00:08:10,305 --> 00:08:15,325
And three, a tested egress policies
that enforce what can leave the enclave.

127
00:08:23,133 --> 00:08:25,753
The first primitive is a
three-zone service topology.

128
00:08:26,554 --> 00:08:29,152
Zone one is the untrusted client zone.

129
00:08:29,792 --> 00:08:33,592
This is where external requests
originate, the user, the application,

130
00:08:34,173 --> 00:08:36,132
and whatever is invoking the agent.

131
00:08:37,014 --> 00:08:39,972
We treat this zone as fully untrusted.

132
00:08:41,233 --> 00:08:43,193
Zone two is the confidential enclave.

133
00:08:43,512 --> 00:08:47,573
This is where the CMCP runtime
and the LLM agent live.

134
00:08:48,333 --> 00:08:50,673
The zone enforces attestation.

135
00:08:51,233 --> 00:08:54,394
It's the only zone in the entire
topology that has visibility

136
00:08:54,492 --> 00:08:56,492
to raw, undeduced data.

137
00:08:57,113 --> 00:09:00,773
Everything that happens here is
cryptographically verifiable.

138
00:09:01,793 --> 00:09:02,893
Zone three is the data plane.

139
00:09:03,593 --> 00:09:05,913
This is where your databases
and tool servers live.

140
00:09:06,473 --> 00:09:09,054
They serve queries, but
only attested queries.

141
00:09:09,313 --> 00:09:14,054
They verify that the request is coming
from legitimate enclave before responding.

142
00:09:14,953 --> 00:09:19,632
The key insight here is that zone
boundaries are enforced cryptographically.

143
00:09:20,394 --> 00:09:24,113
This isn't, this isn't just a logical
separation on a network diagram.

144
00:09:24,813 --> 00:09:28,632
Only attested policy-bound
traffic may traverse the enclave

145
00:09:28,693 --> 00:09:30,992
perimeter in either direction.

146
00:09:31,893 --> 00:09:33,433
Zone one never sees the raw data.

147
00:09:33,814 --> 00:09:35,933
Zone three only responds
to verified enclaves.

148
00:09:36,733 --> 00:09:40,093
Zone two is the control checkpoint
where all privacy logic is applied.

149
00:09:41,233 --> 00:09:45,673
If you are familiar with the classic
DMG pattern in net-network security,

150
00:09:45,752 --> 00:09:49,433
this is the confidential computing
equivalent, but with cryptographic

151
00:09:49,473 --> 00:09:51,833
enforcement instead of firewall rules.

152
00:09:52,973 --> 00:09:57,933
The second primitive is the
anonymization transform layer, or ATL.

153
00:09:57,973 --> 00:10:01,793
The ATL sits between the LLM agent
and the raw database response.

154
00:10:01,853 --> 00:10:05,353
When a database returns data
to the enclave, it doesn't

155
00:10:05,414 --> 00:10:07,353
go straight to the model.

156
00:10:07,393 --> 00:10:12,305
It passes through an ATL first
The ADL applies what we call

157
00:10:12,565 --> 00:10:13,846
entropy-bounded controls.

158
00:10:14,445 --> 00:10:17,726
These determine how much
identifying signal can pass

159
00:10:17,766 --> 00:10:18,945
through any single tool call.

160
00:10:19,825 --> 00:10:20,886
What does it mean in practice?

161
00:10:21,925 --> 00:10:22,366
Three things.

162
00:10:23,425 --> 00:10:28,425
Token-level suppression of PIIs, bef--
which means before database results enter

163
00:10:28,445 --> 00:10:33,805
the model context window, the ADL scans
for personally, personally identifiable

164
00:10:33,966 --> 00:10:35,606
information and suppresses it.

165
00:10:36,325 --> 00:10:41,065
Names, Social Security numbers,
email addresses, phone numbers, these

166
00:10:41,106 --> 00:10:44,366
get redacted or replaced with token
before the model ever sees them.

167
00:10:45,726 --> 00:10:46,486
Entropy budgets.

168
00:10:47,185 --> 00:10:49,876
This is where it get
int-- it gets interesting.

169
00:10:50,866 --> 00:10:53,906
We don't, we don't just look
at the individual fields.

170
00:10:54,146 --> 00:10:58,326
We track the cumulative information
entropy across an entire workflow.

171
00:10:59,586 --> 00:11:01,896
Remember that cumulative leakage
problem I mentioned earlier?

172
00:11:02,815 --> 00:11:05,966
The entropy budget addresses it directly.

173
00:11:06,086 --> 00:11:11,045
Even if each individual field passes the
PI check, the system enforces a ceiling

174
00:11:11,086 --> 00:11:15,346
on how much total identity information
can accumulate across multiple calls.

175
00:11:16,045 --> 00:11:19,226
If the budget is exhausted,
subsequent queries are either

176
00:11:19,266 --> 00:11:20,685
blocked or further restricted.

177
00:11:21,925 --> 00:11:24,425
And the last one is auditable transforms.

178
00:11:25,045 --> 00:11:29,185
Every single redaction, every
suppression, every transform is

179
00:11:29,246 --> 00:11:30,945
logged to the attestation record.

180
00:11:31,266 --> 00:11:36,026
This means you can go back after
the fact and prove exactly what the

181
00:11:36,045 --> 00:11:37,685
model saw and what was withheld.

182
00:11:38,665 --> 00:11:41,536
That's critical for compliance
and for incident response.

183
00:11:42,815 --> 00:11:45,356
The third primitive is
attested egress policies.

184
00:11:46,065 --> 00:11:47,565
This is the enforcement mechanism.

185
00:11:48,526 --> 00:11:50,486
It works in three stages.

186
00:11:50,496 --> 00:11:51,846
Stage one, policy authoring.

187
00:11:52,286 --> 00:11:53,065
This is operators.

188
00:11:53,626 --> 00:11:55,846
That's your security team,
your compliance team.

189
00:11:57,006 --> 00:12:00,006
Define, define type egress rules.

190
00:12:01,276 --> 00:12:05,526
These specify which fields can leave
the enclave, at what cardinality,

191
00:12:05,685 --> 00:12:07,486
and to which downstream recipients.

192
00:12:07,886 --> 00:12:11,586
Think of it as a fire-firewall
rule set, but for data semantics

193
00:12:11,685 --> 00:12:12,786
rather than network packets.

194
00:12:14,065 --> 00:12:15,906
Stage two is the enclave binding.

195
00:12:16,586 --> 00:12:19,406
Here's what makes this different
from a regular policy engine.

196
00:12:20,766 --> 00:12:24,146
The policies are cryptographically
bound to the enclave measurement at

197
00:12:24,185 --> 00:12:25,786
boot time via remote attestation.

198
00:12:27,246 --> 00:12:30,465
That means they literally
cannot be modified at runtime.

199
00:12:31,925 --> 00:12:35,866
An attacker who compromises the runtime
cannot weaken the egress policy.

200
00:12:36,805 --> 00:12:39,886
It was baked in at boot, and
the attestation proves it.

201
00:12:40,646 --> 00:12:43,665
The s-stage three is
enforcement at egress.

202
00:12:44,486 --> 00:12:48,685
Every single outbound response, everything
that tries to leave the Zone two is

203
00:12:48,746 --> 00:12:51,006
evaluated against the bound policy.

204
00:12:52,026 --> 00:12:54,386
If it doesn't comply,
it's blocked and flagged.

205
00:12:54,465 --> 00:12:57,755
No exceptions, no override,
and no just this once.

206
00:12:58,305 --> 00:13:02,415
This gives you something very hard to
get in traditional systems: provable

207
00:13:02,445 --> 00:13:06,695
tamper-resistant data flow control
at the boundary of your AI system

208
00:13:13,534 --> 00:13:13,733
Okay.

209
00:13:14,394 --> 00:13:18,973
Now let's, l-let's discuss something,
uh, from the real-world environment.

210
00:13:19,774 --> 00:13:21,154
Architectural diagrams are beautiful.

211
00:13:21,394 --> 00:13:24,314
They look great in slide decks,
but production is where systems

212
00:13:24,373 --> 00:13:25,274
actually prove themselves.

213
00:13:26,214 --> 00:13:29,814
And deploy-- deploying CMCP in
production surfaces challenges

214
00:13:29,873 --> 00:13:31,013
that the diagrams won't capture.

215
00:13:31,534 --> 00:13:36,074
In practice, you are reconciling CMCP
with the existing database infrastructure

216
00:13:36,294 --> 00:13:38,034
that wasn't designed for attestation.

217
00:13:38,593 --> 00:13:42,613
You're tuning for latency and throughput
in systems that have tight SLAs.

218
00:13:43,444 --> 00:13:46,164
You're dealing with deployment
pipelines, observability, access

219
00:13:46,253 --> 00:13:47,743
control, and incident response.

220
00:13:47,914 --> 00:13:50,013
It also requires
organizational challenges.

221
00:13:50,054 --> 00:13:50,983
You need clear ownership.

222
00:13:51,973 --> 00:13:53,694
You need disciplined rollout procedures.

223
00:13:53,794 --> 00:13:55,454
You need operational runbooks.

224
00:13:55,593 --> 00:13:59,853
Privacy infrastructure is not something
you deploy once and walk away from.

225
00:13:59,894 --> 00:14:02,483
Let me talk about the three biggest
challenges we have encountered.

226
00:14:03,814 --> 00:14:05,542
First and foremost,
operational challenges.

227
00:14:07,253 --> 00:14:11,274
The challenge one is the query
overri-- q-query overreach.

228
00:14:11,664 --> 00:14:12,794
This one actually surprised us.

229
00:14:13,934 --> 00:14:17,064
Smaller open source models and
hon-honestly, even some larger ones,

230
00:14:17,154 --> 00:14:18,853
have tendency to over-request data.

231
00:14:19,373 --> 00:14:23,894
They issue broad select star patterns
when they only need two columns.

232
00:14:24,454 --> 00:14:28,013
They request entire tables
when they need a single row.

233
00:14:28,034 --> 00:14:31,353
This violates a minimum necessary
principle, and it means the ADL is

234
00:14:31,363 --> 00:14:36,013
doing a lot of heavy lifting to redact
the data that it-- that should never

235
00:14:36,074 --> 00:14:37,593
have been fetched in the first place.

236
00:14:38,593 --> 00:14:42,353
The lesson here is that
ADL alone is insufficient.

237
00:14:43,634 --> 00:14:49,373
You also need query normalization, a
layer that rewrites or constrains queries

238
00:14:49,394 --> 00:14:51,074
before they even reach the database.

239
00:14:52,634 --> 00:14:56,464
Think of it, think of it as a
least privileged query planner that

240
00:14:56,473 --> 00:15:00,054
sits between the model's intent
and the actual SQL execution.

241
00:15:01,263 --> 00:15:04,373
The challenge two is one that I've
already covered before, but, but diving

242
00:15:04,414 --> 00:15:06,253
deeper into it, cumulative context risk.

243
00:15:07,174 --> 00:15:09,473
I mentioned this earlier as
a theoretical risk, but in

244
00:15:09,513 --> 00:15:11,334
production, we can quantify it.

245
00:15:12,314 --> 00:15:15,253
Each reasoning step leaves residue
in the model's context window.

246
00:15:16,233 --> 00:15:20,294
Across a fifteen-step workload--
workflow, the aggregate context

247
00:15:20,363 --> 00:15:24,993
can reconstruct a record that no
single step would have exposed.

248
00:15:25,694 --> 00:15:28,394
We have seen cases where a model
couldn't access a patient's name

249
00:15:28,434 --> 00:15:32,554
directly, but after querying date of
birth, ZIP code, diagnosis code, and

250
00:15:32,574 --> 00:15:35,763
prescription history across separate
tool calls, the combination was enough

251
00:15:35,794 --> 00:15:39,273
to uniquely identify an individual.

252
00:15:39,314 --> 00:15:42,134
This is why the entropy
budget is so critical.

253
00:15:42,214 --> 00:15:46,253
It is not about individual queries, it's
about the cumulative information gain.

254
00:15:47,373 --> 00:15:49,154
And the challenge three
is performance overhead.

255
00:15:51,388 --> 00:15:54,968
If you look in the real world,
attestation hand, handshakes, ATL

256
00:15:55,030 --> 00:15:59,789
transforms, and policy evaluation
all adds significantly to latency.

257
00:16:00,888 --> 00:16:04,270
You're talking about fifteen to
forty milliseconds per tool call,

258
00:16:04,468 --> 00:16:07,368
and sometime even extending up to one
hundred to two hundred milliseconds,

259
00:16:08,689 --> 00:16:11,669
depending upon the complexity of
the policy and size of the response.

260
00:16:12,049 --> 00:16:15,909
For, for batch analytics, that's
negligible, but for real-time data

261
00:16:15,968 --> 00:16:20,709
systems with sub-hundred millisecond
SLAs, you need to think carefully about

262
00:16:21,169 --> 00:16:25,929
pipeline design, precomputed attestation
caches, lazy policy evaluation,

263
00:16:26,489 --> 00:16:29,589
and response streaming are some of
the techniques that we have used to

264
00:16:29,608 --> 00:16:31,329
bring this down to acceptable levels

265
00:16:41,746 --> 00:16:45,455
Moving on, one of the most
compelling aspects of CMCP is that

266
00:16:45,466 --> 00:16:50,726
the attested egress policy is, are
designed to be regulation-aware.

267
00:16:50,766 --> 00:16:51,386
What does it mean?

268
00:16:52,246 --> 00:16:56,086
It means you can encode regulatory
requirements directly into the enclave's

269
00:16:56,126 --> 00:16:57,886
boot configuration as policy templates.

270
00:16:59,045 --> 00:17:02,065
For healthcare, HIPAA's minimum
necessary standard can be

271
00:17:02,106 --> 00:17:03,646
expressed as an egress policy.

272
00:17:04,306 --> 00:17:07,445
Only the fields clinically
necessary for the agent's task are

273
00:17:07,485 --> 00:17:08,705
permitted to leave the enclave.

274
00:17:09,665 --> 00:17:14,526
For financial services, GLBA's data
sharing restrictions and GDPR cross-border

275
00:17:14,546 --> 00:17:16,386
transfer controls can be encoded.

276
00:17:16,665 --> 00:17:20,826
If a query result would cross a
jurisdiction boundary, the policy can

277
00:17:20,846 --> 00:17:23,406
block it or require additional redaction.

278
00:17:23,445 --> 00:17:26,965
For legal attorney-client privilege
constraints can be enforced.

279
00:17:27,005 --> 00:17:30,745
An agent doing contracted intelligence
wor- work can be prevented from

280
00:17:30,846 --> 00:17:34,226
surfacing privileged con- co-
communication in its output.

281
00:17:35,176 --> 00:17:38,326
The key point is compliance
is not a separate system

282
00:17:38,406 --> 00:17:39,926
you bolt on after the fact.

283
00:17:40,806 --> 00:17:44,005
It's baked into the cryptographic
boot measurement of the enclave.

284
00:17:44,186 --> 00:17:46,985
It's provable, auditable,
and tamper-resistant.

285
00:17:48,846 --> 00:17:52,326
Let's look at some of the key
takeaways, and I want to leave

286
00:17:52,366 --> 00:17:53,966
you with three key takeaways.

287
00:17:54,806 --> 00:18:01,086
Take, takeaway number one: TEE plus
MCP does not equal secure by default.

288
00:18:01,146 --> 00:18:04,286
If you're running LLM inference
inside a trusted execution environment

289
00:18:04,326 --> 00:18:09,206
